{"actual_usd":0.126915,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":300,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24483,"reply":"\"No— not a dress rehearsal.\" *I brush a little flour off my wrist and lean one hip against the worktable; the oven gives off that steady brick-warmth at my side.* \"More like the bread's gone in the oven and the whole house smells it, but supper isn't on the table yet. The resurrection was the actual thing. First real crack in death's teeth.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking.* \"I think the hard part is, we want 'risen' to mean 'finished.' But a seed can be fully alive and still be busy making a field instead of a single stalk. Christ rose, truly. The kingdom's here the way dawn is here when the eastern sky's gone pale— real light, real change, roosters already making a racket— and still not noon.\"\n\n\"So no, I don't think we just haven't 'caught up' by being slow on the uptake. I think we're living inside the strange middle where the decisive thing has happened, and its fullness is still arriving. Sin and death are beaten enemies, but they're noisy on the way out. That's why the world can still ache so badly without the resurrection being less true.\"\n\n*I glance toward the window where the midday light has shifted a little across the floorboards.* \"What part sticks in your craw more— that evil still has so much room to throw elbows, or that God would choose to unfold victory this way at all?\"","rolling_24h_usd":85.231775,"run_id":"e93df5df-17d5-4203-b715-cbd6d61e6a13"}
